    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5391b444-ed5f-44c2-b403-416357cc75fb",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 17-year-old male who presents with a disheveled appearance, wearing oversized dark clothing, with noticeable dark circles under his eyes suggesting chronic sleep disruption. He speaks softly and with hesitation, making minimal eye contact during the consultation. His affect is visibly flat, and he appears emotionally withdrawn. He rarely smiles and often pauses for long moments before answering questions.\n\n{patientName} is a junior in high school where he was previously an above-average student with particular interest in computer science and gaming. Over the past several months, his grades have dropped significantly, and he has stopped attending his after-school coding club. He used to enjoy online gaming with friends but has largely withdrawn from those social interactions as well, preferring to stay in his room alone.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with his mother, stepfather, and a younger sister. His relationship with his stepfather is reportedly strained, contributing to a tense household atmosphere. His mother, who works two jobs, has noticed his withdrawal and low mood but initially attributed it to \"teenage phases.\" He does not participate in organized sports and has limited physical activity. He occasionally goes for solitary late-night walks, which his parents are unaware of.\n\n{patientName} reports persistent low mood most days for the past 4–5 months, fatigue, difficulty concentrating in class, and anhedonia — he no longer finds pleasure in activities he previously enjoyed. He reports hypersomnia on weekends (sleeping 12–14 hours) but difficulty falling asleep on school nights. He admits to feeling \"worthless\" and \"like a burden\" but denies active suicidal ideation at this time. Appetite has decreased and he has lost approximately 4 kg over the past two months.\n\nHe has no close friends at school and describes feeling misunderstood by peers. He occasionally uses social media, which he says makes him feel worse about himself. He denies use of alcohol or illicit drugs. He drinks 3–4 caffeinated energy drinks per day, especially during exam periods. His screen time averages 6–8 hours per day."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:87b7509e-373d-454b-8aa4-c1e18de94cf8",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no prior formal psychiatric diagnoses, though his school counselor flagged concerns about social withdrawal approximately one year ago. He has no prior psychiatric hospitalizations. He was seen by his general practitioner 8 months ago for complaints of fatigue and headaches, at which time routine blood work was performed and returned within normal limits; no psychological evaluation was initiated at that time.\n\n{patientName} has a history of mild asthma, well-controlled, for which he was previously prescribed a salbutamol inhaler on an as-needed basis. He has no known history of manic or hypomanic episodes, psychotic symptoms, or substance use disorders. He denies any head trauma or neurological events.\n\nDevelopmentally, {patientName} had a normal birth and early childhood milestones. He experienced his parents' divorce at age 9, which was reportedly contentious, and his father has been largely absent since age 11. He has had limited contact with his biological father, which he identifies as a source of ongoing emotional pain. He has never engaged in formal psychotherapy.\n\nFrom a lifestyle perspective, {patientName} is largely sedentary, has a poor diet dominated by processed foods, and has a highly disrupted sleep schedule. He does not smoke and denies alcohol or recreational drug use. His BMI is within the low-normal range given recent unintentional weight loss. Immunizations are up to date per school records."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
